  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Supporting vulnerable girls and boys regain access to education due to COVID-19-related school closures in Jawzjan, Afghanistan.</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Since March 2020, due to COVID-19, Afghanistan has closed its schools for five months leaving 7.5 million children with no access to education. Alternative modalities were put in place to provide education to children, including distance education (through television, radio), self-learning and small group learning but these relied heavily on access to electricity and/or technology, leaving the most vulnerable behind. With the rate of new cases decreasing, the Ministry of Education has started to allow schools to reopen as long as they meet minimum requirements to allow a safe return to learning, including comprehensive protocols and strict hygiene measures to prevent the transmission of COVID- 19. In response to this, ACTED will provide support to 80 schools and 13 CBCs in Mingajik, Aqcha and Fayzabad districts of Jawzjan, reaching 43,174 women, men, boys and girls.


The response will provide 58 primary and secondary schools and 13 CBCs with access to handwashing stations with soap and potable water plus WASH and disinfection kits. In addition, ACTED will provide 43,174 boy and girl students, women and men teachers with two washable, reusable facemasks each across 80 schools and 13 CBCs.


As CBE and schools are unlikely to be able to open straightaway in every case, ACTED will also provide 5,736 vulnerable Grade 1-3 children with self-learning materials so they are able to regain access to education as quickly as possible.</narrative>
  </description>
